## ðŸ”¥ Substitution Method Practice Questions with Solutions

---

### **Q1.**

Solve using substitution method:

$$
T(n) = T(n-1) + 1, \quad T(1) = 1
$$

**Solution:**
Expand karte hain:

$$
T(n) = T(n-1) + 1
$$

$$
= (T(n-2) + 1) + 1
$$

$$
= T(n-2) + 2
$$

$$
= T(n-3) + 3
$$

â€¦

$$
= T(1) + (n-1)
$$

$$
= 1 + (n-1) = n
$$

âœ… Final:

$$
T(n) = O(n)
$$

---

### **Q2.**

$$
T(n) = T(n/2) + 1, \quad T(1) = 1
$$

**Solution:**
Expand:

$$
T(n) = T(n/2) + 1
$$

$$
= T(n/4) + 1 + 1
$$

$$
= T(n/8) + 3
$$

After $k$ steps:

$$
T(n) = T(n/2^k) + k
$$

Stop when $n/2^k = 1 \Rightarrow 2^k = n \Rightarrow k = \log_2 n$.

So:

$$
T(n) = T(1) + \log_2 n = 1 + \log_2 n
$$

âœ… Final:

$$
T(n) = O(\log n)
$$

---

### **Q3.**

$$
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + n, \quad T(1) = 1
$$

**Solution:**
Expand:

$$
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + n
$$

$$
= 2[2T(n/4) + n/2] + n
$$

$$
= 4T(n/4) + n + n
$$

$$
= 4T(n/4) + 2n
$$

$$
= 8T(n/8) + 3n
$$

General form after $k$ steps:

$$
T(n) = 2^k T(n/2^k) + kn
$$

Stop when $n/2^k = 1 \Rightarrow k = \log n$.

$$
T(n) = nT(1) + n\log n = n + n\log n
$$

âœ… Final:

$$
T(n) = O(n \log n)
$$

---

### **Q4.**

$$
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + 1, \quad T(1) = 1
$$

**Solution:**
Expand:

$$
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + 1
$$

$$
= 2[2T(n/4) + 1] + 1
$$

$$
= 4T(n/4) + 2 + 1
$$

$$
= 8T(n/8) + 4 + 2 + 1
$$

After $k$ steps:

$$
T(n) = 2^k T(n/2^k) + (2^k - 1)
$$

When $n/2^k = 1 \Rightarrow k = \log n$:

$$
T(n) = nT(1) + (n-1) = n + n - 1
$$

âœ… Final:

$$
T(n) = O(n)
$$

---

### **Q5.**

$$
T(n) = T(n-1) + n, \quad T(1) = 1
$$

**Solution:**
Expand:

$$
T(n) = T(n-1) + n
$$

$$
= (T(n-2) + (n-1)) + n
$$

$$
= T(n-2) + (n-1) + n
$$

$$
= T(n-3) + (n-2) + (n-1) + n
$$

$$
= T(1) + (2+3+...+n)
$$

$$
T(n) = 1 + \frac{n(n+1)}{2} - 1 = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}
$$

âœ… Final:

$$
T(n) = O(n^2)
$$

---

### **Q6. (Tougher one)**

$$
T(n) = 3T(n/2) + n, \quad T(1)=1
$$

**Solution:**
Expand:

$$
T(n) = 3T(n/2) + n
$$

$$
= 3[3T(n/4) + n/2] + n
$$

$$
= 9T(n/4) + \tfrac{3n}{2} + n
$$

$$
= 27T(n/8) + \tfrac{7n}{2}
$$

After $k$ steps:

$$
T(n) = 3^k T(n/2^k) + n\left(\frac{3^k-1}{2}\right)
$$

When $n/2^k = 1 \Rightarrow k = \log_2 n$:

$$
T(n) = 3^{\log_2 n} \cdot T(1) + n\cdot \frac{3^{\log_2 n}-1}{2}
$$

Note: $3^{\log_2 n} = n^{\log_2 3}$.

$$
T(n) = n^{\log_2 3} + \frac{n}{2}(n^{\log_2 3} - 1)
$$

âœ… Final:

$$
T(n) = O\left(n^{\log_2 3}\right) \approx O(n^{1.58})
$$

---

âš¡ These 6 types cover **almost every recurrence** tumhare lab eval ke liye (linear, logarithmic, n log n, quadratic, fractional exponents).

